pragma language_version >= 0.16 && <= 0.23;

import CompactStandardLibrary;

// ============================================================================
// CTO GOVERNANCE PSM — Noctis Protocol
// ============================================================================
//
// Community Takeover Opportunity (CTO) governance system.
//
// When a creator goes MIA (90+ days no claim + no social post), the community
// can vote to trigger a CTO. After CTO trigger:
//   - Creator's future bonding-curve trade fees redirect to a community
//     wallet (as of T51, 2026-07-12: this happens directly on each tier's
//     own bonding curve contract — bonding_curve.ak/bonding_curve_tier_b.ak/
//     bonding_curve.compact's own triggerCTO — NOT via creator_escrow.compact,
//     which never actually receives real fee deposits in the current
//     architecture; see that file's header and internal tracking)
//   - LP escrow migration authority transfers to community wallet
//   - DEX whitelist management transfers to community wallet
//   - Unvested creator tokens freeze to community treasury
//
// This contract (cto_governance) only ever flips its OWN ctoState/
// communityWallet when a proposal executes — it cannot call any other
// PSM's triggerCTO directly (Compact has no cross-contract call mechanism,
// T2/T25). Each dependent contract's own triggerCTO must be called as a
// separate, off-chain-orchestrated transaction — see
// integration/midnight-client.ts's executeCtoProposal.
//
// This is NOT a kill switch — it's a living governance mechanism:
//   - Ongoing community proposals after CTO (fund allocation, DEX migration)
//   - Per-token weighted voting (balance from bonding curve PSM)
//   - Private voting via nullifier pattern (prevent double-vote, protect privacy)
//   - 72-hour ballot window, 5% quorum, simple majority
//   - 90-day cooldown after any vote
//   - 30-day post-graduation minimum before first proposal
//
// Jinx's vision: "Features that help with CTOs, not just have keys and LP
// burned." The community gets TOOLS to keep the project alive, not just
// a nuclear option.
//
// BREAK-GLASS FALLBACK (2026-07-19): createProposal's SilenceLockTrigger
// branch requires hasClaimableBalance == true (T36) before a vote can even
// be proposed — but that field is governor-attested off-chain (this
// contract has no cross-contract read into the real fee-holding curve
// contract, T2/T25). A compromised, absent, or malicious governor could
// therefore refuse to ever confirm a real claimable balance exists,
// permanently blocking the community from ever proposing a CTO — a
// single-point-of-failure that contradicts the whole premise of this
// contract being a COMMUNITY-triggered process. bondedSilenceChallenge /
// resolveBreakGlassChallenge / claimBreakGlassBondRefund below give the
// community a bonded, permissionless override of that one gate:
//   1. Anyone can post a NIGHT bond asserting hasClaimableBalance should be
//      true, once the creator is already independently, publicly silent
//      long enough (checked against the real elapsed time since
//      lastCreatorActivity — break-glass never shortens the silence
//      timer itself, only bypasses the balance attestation).
//   2. The governor gets a fixed response window (72h, same as a normal
//      ballot) to weigh in — a genuine, timestamped updateCreatorActivity
//      call during or after that window that still shows no claimable
//      balance counts as a real rebuttal and forfeits the bond (60/40
//      treasury/ops, matching every other forfeiture in this codebase).
//   3. If the governor never touches updateCreatorActivity at all during
//      the window (true unresponsiveness/censorship), the challenge
//      auto-confirms once the window elapses: hasClaimableBalance is
//      force-set true and the challenger's bond is refunded in full.
// This deliberately does NOT bypass the separate balanceSnapshotRoot gate
// on createProposal (every proposal type, not just SilenceLockTrigger) —
// that root is what makes castVote's balance proof forgery-proof
// ; breaking THAT glass would reopen the vote-weight-forgery
// hole it was built to close. balanceSnapshotRoot governor-censorship risk
// is a separate, harder problem, tracked independently rather than solved
// here (see internal tracking).
//
// Reuses patterns from:
//   - midnight-modules/voting (ballot lifecycle, nullifier voting)
//   - midnight-modules/commitment-nullifier (double-vote prevention)
//   - midnight-modules/access-control (governor + community wallet)
//   - realVote/zvoting (per-election nullifier, POL-gated voting)
//   - midnight-expert FungibleToken (witness-derived identity)
//
// Compiler: compactc v0.31.1
// ============================================================================

// ============================================================================
// DATA STRUCTURES
// ============================================================================

export enum CtoState { PreCTO, CTOTriggered, CTODissolved }

export enum ProposalType {
  SilenceLockTrigger,    // Initial CTO trigger (creator MIA 90+ days)
  FundAllocation,        // Allocate community treasury funds
  DexMigration,          // Migrate LP to a new DEX
  WhitelistUpdate,       // Add/remove DEX from whitelist
  DissolveCTO            // Dissolve CTO (return control to creator if they return)
}

// T-AUDIT note (2026-07-21, Low): `Pending` is never assigned anywhere in
// this file — createProposal sets new proposals directly to `Active`
// (the balanceSnapshotRoot/quorum/silence checks it already runs make a
// separate not-yet-open state unnecessary). Kept in the enum for now since
// removing a variant changes the generated type across every TS consumer;
// dead but harmless.
export enum ProposalState { Pending, Active, Passed, Failed, Executed }

// Break-glass challenge lifecycle — see the file header's BREAK-GLASS
// FALLBACK note for the full design.
export enum BreakGlassState { None, Pending, Confirmed, Rebutted }

export struct UserSecretKey { bytes: Bytes<32>; }
export struct UserPublicKey { bytes: Bytes<32>; }

export struct Proposal {
  proposalType: ProposalType;
  proposerKey: Bytes<32>;
  descriptionHash: Bytes<32>;   // Hash of off-chain proposal description
  startTimestamp: Uint<64>;
  endTimestamp: Uint<64>;       // startTimestamp + 72h
  yesVotes: Uint<128>;          // Total token-weight of YES votes
  noVotes: Uint<128>;           // Total token-weight of NO votes
  voterCount: Uint<64>;         // Number of unique voters
  state: ProposalState;
  // Creator vote audit tracking (T35 resolution)
  creatorYesVotes: Uint<128>;  // Creator's YES vote weight (capped at 2% supply)
  creatorNoVotes: Uint<128>;   // Creator's NO vote weight (capped at 2% supply)
  // Execution payload — what happens when proposal passes
  targetDexAddr: Bytes<32>;     // For DexMigration / WhitelistUpdate
  allocationAmount: Uint<128>;  // For FundAllocation
  allocationRecipient: Bytes<32>; // For FundAllocation
  // Security audit fix: pinned at createProposal time so executeProposal
  // can no longer accept an attacker-chosen wallet at execution time —
  // only meaningful for SilenceLockTrigger, harmless (zero) otherwise.
  proposedCommunityWallet: Bytes<32>;
  // Security audit fix: the balance-snapshot Merkle root this proposal's
  // votes are checked against, pinned at creation so a governor publishing
  // a new snapshot mid-ballot can't change what an in-flight vote proves.
  balanceSnapshotRoot: Bytes<32>;
}

// A single, per-launch break-glass challenge slot — one active challenge
// at a time (mirrors how rare this path should be; a real challenge only
// happens when the normal governor-attestation path has already failed).
export struct BreakGlassChallenge {
  challenger: Bytes<32>;
  bondAmount: Uint<128>;
  challengeTimestamp: Uint<64>;
  state: BreakGlassState;
}

struct ProposalIdInput {
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  proposerKey: Bytes<32>;
  descriptionHash: Bytes<32>;
  timestamp: Uint<64>;
}

struct VoteNullifierInput {
  voterKey: Bytes<32>;
  launchId: Bytes<32>;
  proposalId: Bytes<32>;
}

// One level of a Merkle inclusion proof for the balance snapshot — same
// fixed-depth-tree convention as bonding_curve.compact's T42 allowlist
// proof (sibling + direction bit per level, 20 levels always, no early
// exit since `fold` can't branch on tree size). Depth reduced 32 -> 20,
// T64, 2026-07-12 — see getBalanceProof's witness declaration comment.
struct MerkleProofEntry {
  sibling: Bytes<32>;
  goesLeft: Boolean;
}

// Domain-separated leaf: binds a real token balance to the voter's own
// derived identity so a balance can't be "borrowed" from someone else's
// leaf the way an unbound allowlist leaf could (security audit fix).
struct BalanceLeafInput {
  domain: Bytes<32>;
  voterKey: Bytes<32>;
  balance: Uint<128>;
}

// Domain-separated Merkle node hash for the balance-snapshot tree.
struct BalanceNodeInput {
  domain: Bytes<32>;
  left: Bytes<32>;
  right: Bytes<32>;
}

// ============================================================================
// LEDGER STATE
// ============================================================================

sealed ledger launchId: Bytes<32>;

// CTO governance state
export ledger ctoState: CtoState;

// Community wallet — receives redirected fees after CTO trigger
// Set when CTO is triggered, used for all future fund flows
export ledger communityWallet: Bytes<32>;

// Creator's last activity timestamp (claim or social post)
// Updated by governor from off-chain monitoring
export ledger lastCreatorActivity: Uint<64>;

// Whether the launch's bonding-curve fee escrow (Stream A) currently holds
// a real, unclaimed balance — governor-attested from off-chain monitoring
// of the actual fee-holding contract (bonding_curve.compact for Tier C,
// bonding_curve_tier_b.ak for Tier B; this contract has no cross-contract
// call mechanism to check either directly, T2/T25). T36 fix (2026-07-12):
// without this, a zero-volume launch (no trade fees ever accrued) could
// still have SilenceLockTrigger proposed and passed purely on elapsed
// time, triggering a CTO vote over nothing — there would be no balance to
// "recover" for the community. Same governor-trust boundary already
// accepted for lastCreatorActivity, not a new one — updated together via
// updateCreatorActivity, since both facts come from the same off-chain
// source (watching the curve contract).
export ledger hasClaimableBalance: Boolean;

// Graduation timestamp — proposals can't be submitted until 30 days after
sealed ledger graduationTimestamp: Uint<64>;

// Total token supply (for quorum calculation)
sealed ledger totalSupply: Uint<128>;

// Silence lock threshold in seconds (90 days = 7776000)
sealed ledger silenceThreshold: Uint<64>;

// Cooldown duration after any vote (90 days = 7776000)
sealed ledger cooldownDuration: Uint<64>;

// Minimum delay after graduation before first proposal (30 days = 2592000)
sealed ledger minPostGradDelay: Uint<64>;

// Ballot duration (72 hours = 259200)
sealed ledger ballotDuration: Uint<64>;

// Quorum threshold in basis points (500 = 5% of total supply)
sealed ledger quorumBps: Uint<16>;

// Creator vote weight cap, as an absolute token amount (e.g. 2% of total
// supply pre-computed off-chain) — set directly via the constructor rather
// than stored as basis points, since `creatorVoteCapBps` was declared here
// but never assigned in the constructor (defaulting to 0, silently zeroing
// every creator-flagged vote) and the bps-based version this replaced
// multiplied by totalSupply with no /10000 divisor, the same missing-
// division bug fixed in eligibility_gate.compact's walletCap (2026-07-09).
sealed ledger creatorVoteCap: Uint<128>;

// Last proposal end timestamp (for cooldown enforcement)
export ledger lastProposalEnd: Uint<64>;

// Active proposals keyed by proposal ID
export ledger proposals: Map<Bytes<32>, Proposal>;

// Vote nullifiers — prevents double-voting per proposal
export ledger voteNullifiers: Set<Bytes<32>>;

// Proposal counter
export ledger proposalCount: Counter;

// Governor key (platform admin, can update creator activity timestamps)
sealed ledger governorKey: Bytes<32>;

// Creator's identity, same UserPublicKey domain regular voters derive
// under. Security audit fix: previously castVote took `isCreator` as a
// free caller-supplied Boolean; now it's derived in-circuit by comparing
// against this pinned key, same pattern as every other PSM's creator check.
sealed ledger creatorKey: Bytes<32>;

// Governor-published Merkle root of (voterKey, balance) leaves — security
// audit fix for the vote-weight-forgery finding. Compact has no working
// cross-contract call mechanism (see witnesses.ts's cross-PSM composition
// note), so `castVote` can't read a real balance from the bonding curve
// PSM directly. Governor periodically snapshots real holdings off-chain
// and publishes the root here; each proposal pins whatever root is current
// at creation time (see Proposal.balanceSnapshotRoot) so voters prove
// their real balance via Merkle proof instead of just asserting a number.
export ledger balanceSnapshotRoot: Bytes<32>;

// Real wall-clock time the CURRENT balanceSnapshotRoot was published —
// stale-snapshot fix (2026-07-19). Before this, createProposal only
// checked balanceSnapshotRoot was non-empty (SOME snapshot exists, ever)
// with no check on how OLD it is. A governor could publish one snapshot
// early on and never refresh it again; every subsequent proposal for
// months or years would still weight votes against real holdings that had
// long since drifted — someone who sold their entire stake right after
// the snapshot keeps full voting power under it, someone who bought a
// large stake afterward gets none. maxSnapshotAge/createProposal's new
// check below bound how stale a snapshot can be before a NEW proposal can
// be created against it (existing proposals already pin their own root at
// creation time and are unaffected once created).
export ledger lastSnapshotTimestamp: Uint<64>;

// Fixed platform policy constant — hardcoded in the constructor body, same
// convention as ballotDuration/silenceThreshold. 30 days (2592000s),
// matching minPostGradDelay's own value: tight enough that a genuinely
// abandoned/censoring governor can't coast on a year-old snapshot, loose
// enough not to demand near-continuous republishing for a quiet launch.
sealed ledger maxSnapshotAge: Uint<64>;

// ----------------------------------------------------------------------
// Break-glass fallback (see file header's BREAK-GLASS FALLBACK note)
// ----------------------------------------------------------------------

// Minimum NIGHT bond required to open a break-glass challenge — launch-
// specific (set at deploy, mirrors creatorVoteCap's own per-launch sizing)
// rather than a hardcoded platform constant, since a sensible bond floor
// scales with the launch's own economics. CLAUDE.md does not yet name a
// canonical USD/NIGHT figure for this the way it does for
// NHOP_CHALLENGE_BOND — flagged as a follow-up, not invented here.
sealed ledger breakGlassBondMin: Uint<128>;

// Fixed platform policy constant, not a per-launch choice — same 72-hour
// window as a normal ballot (ballotDuration), giving the governor the same
// amount of time to respond as the community gets to vote.
sealed ledger breakGlassResponseWindow: Uint<64>;

// Fixed payout destinations for a forfeited (rebutted) break-glass bond —
// same 60/40 treasury/ops split convention as every other forfeiture in
// this codebase (T33). This contract had no such fields before; added
// specifically to support break-glass forfeiture payouts.
sealed ledger treasuryAddr: Bytes<32>;
sealed ledger opsAddr: Bytes<32>;

// Real wall-clock time of the governor's LAST updateCreatorActivity call —
// distinct from lastCreatorActivity (the CREATOR's attested activity
// time). A governor who never touches updateCreatorActivity at all leaves
// this frozen at its constructor value regardless of how much real time
// passes, which is exactly the signal resolveBreakGlassChallenge checks
// for genuine unresponsiveness.
export ledger lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp: Uint<64>;

// The current (or most recently resolved) break-glass challenge, if any.
export ledger breakGlassChallenge: BreakGlassChallenge;

// ============================================================================
// WITNESSES
// ============================================================================

witness getUserSecret(): UserSecretKey;
witness getGovernorSecret(): UserSecretKey;

// Voter's real token balance at snapshot time — private, disclosed only
// as the vote weight itself (which was already public before this fix).
witness getBalanceLeafAmount(): Uint<128>;

// Merkle proof that (voter identity, balance) is a leaf in the currently
// pinned balanceSnapshotRoot — private, stays with the prover.
// Depth reduced 32 -> 20 (2026-07-12, T64): a fixed-depth proof always
// walks every level regardless of real holder count, so depth is a direct
// proving-cost lever, not just a capacity ceiling. 2^20 (1,048,576) token
// holders is far beyond any realistic single launch's voter base, for
// 37.5% fewer hash operations per proof than the original 32.
witness getBalanceProof(): Vector<20, MerkleProofEntry>;

// ============================================================================
// HELPER CIRCUITS
// ============================================================================

pure circuit deriveUserPublicKey(sk: UserSecretKey): UserPublicKey {
  return UserPublicKey {
    bytes: persistentHash<Vector<2, Bytes<32>>>([
      pad(32, "noctis:cto:user:pk:v1"),
      sk.bytes
    ])
  };
}

pure circuit deriveGovernorKey(sk: UserSecretKey): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<Vector<2, Bytes<32>>>([
    pad(32, "noctis:cto:governor:pk:v1"),
    sk.bytes
  ]);
}

pure circuit computeProposalId(
  proposer: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>,
  descHash: Bytes<32>,
  timestamp: Uint<64>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<ProposalIdInput>(ProposalIdInput {
    launchId: launch,
    proposerKey: proposer,
    descriptionHash: descHash,
    timestamp: timestamp
  });
}

pure circuit computeVoteNullifier(
  voterKey: Bytes<32>,
  launch: Bytes<32>,
  proposalId: Bytes<32>
): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<VoteNullifierInput>(VoteNullifierInput {
    voterKey: voterKey,
    launchId: launch,
    proposalId: proposalId
  });
}

// One Merkle tree node hash for the balance-snapshot proof — same
// left/right-by-direction-bit fold body as bonding_curve.compact's
// verifyAllowlist, domain-separated so it can never collide with any
// other persistentHash use in this contract.
pure circuit hashBalanceNode(left: Bytes<32>, right: Bytes<32>): Bytes<32> {
  return persistentHash<BalanceNodeInput>(BalanceNodeInput {
    domain: pad(32, "noctis:cto:balance:node:v1"),
    left: left,
    right: right
  });
}

// Verify a claimed fee slice is the FLOOR of grossAmount * bps / 10000 —
// same pattern as eligibility_gate.compact's copy (T39/T33). Compact
// contracts don't share helpers across files, so this is a deliberate,
// verbatim duplicate, not drift — needed here for
// resolveBreakGlassChallenge's forfeited-bond treasury/ops split.
pure circuit verifyFeeSlice(
  grossAmount: Uint<128>,
  bps: Uint<16>,
  claimedFee: Uint<128>
): Boolean {
  assert(disclose(grossAmount <= 19342813113834066795298815), "grossAmount exceeds safe range"); // 2^84 - 1
  assert(disclose(claimedFee <= 19342813113834066795298815), "claimedFee exceeds safe range"); // 2^84 - 1

  const grossN = grossAmount as Uint<84>;
  const claimedFeeN = claimedFee as Uint<84>;

  const product = ((grossN as Uint<100>) * (bps as Uint<100>)) as Uint<100>;
  const claimedTimesDenom = ((claimedFeeN as Uint<98>) * (10000 as Uint<98>)) as Uint<98>;
  const nextClaimedTimesDenom = ((claimedTimesDenom as Uint<100>) + (10000 as Uint<100>)) as Uint<100>;

  return disclose(
    (claimedTimesDenom as Uint<100>) <= product && product < nextClaimedTimesDenom
  );
}

// ============================================================================
// CONSTRUCTOR
// ============================================================================

constructor(
  launchId_: Bytes<32>,
  totalSupply_: Uint<128>,
  graduationTimestamp_: Uint<64>,
  creatorVoteCap_: Uint<128>,
  creatorPubKey_: Bytes<32>,
  hasClaimableBalance_: Boolean,
  breakGlassBondMin_: Uint<128>,
  treasuryAddr_: Bytes<32>,
  opsAddr_: Bytes<32>
) {
  launchId = disclose(launchId_);
  totalSupply = disclose(totalSupply_);
  graduationTimestamp = disclose(graduationTimestamp_);
  assert(disclose(creatorVoteCap_ > 0 && creatorVoteCap_ <= totalSupply_), "creatorVoteCap must be a positive fraction of totalSupply");
  creatorVoteCap = disclose(creatorVoteCap_);
  creatorKey = disclose(creatorPubKey_);
  assert(disclose(breakGlassBondMin_ > 0), "breakGlassBondMin must be positive");
  breakGlassBondMin = disclose(breakGlassBondMin_);
  treasuryAddr = disclose(treasuryAddr_);
  opsAddr = disclose(opsAddr_);

  // Default thresholds
  silenceThreshold = disclose(7776000);   // 90 days
  cooldownDuration = disclose(7776000);   // 90 days
  minPostGradDelay = disclose(2592000);   // 30 days
  ballotDuration = disclose(259200);      // 72 hours
  quorumBps = disclose(500);              // 5%
  breakGlassResponseWindow = disclose(259200); // 72 hours, same as ballotDuration
  maxSnapshotAge = disclose(2592000);     // 30 days

  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  governorKey = disclose(deriveGovernorKey(govSecret));

  ctoState = CtoState.PreCTO;
  lastCreatorActivity = disclose(graduationTimestamp_);
  lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp = disclose(graduationTimestamp_);
  hasClaimableBalance = disclose(hasClaimableBalance_);
  lastProposalEnd = 0;
  communityWallet = disclose(pad(32, ""));
  // No proposal can be created until the governor publishes a real balance
  // snapshot (see createProposal's assert and updateBalanceSnapshot below).
  balanceSnapshotRoot = disclose(pad(32, ""));
  lastSnapshotTimestamp = disclose(0);
  breakGlassChallenge = disclose(BreakGlassChallenge {
    challenger: pad(32, ""),
    bondAmount: 0,
    challengeTimestamp: 0,
    state: BreakGlassState.None
  });
}

// Governor publishes a fresh Merkle root of (voterKey, balance) leaves.
// Design requirement: this is what makes castVote's balance
// proof meaningful — see the ledger field's comment for the full design.
// Stale-snapshot fix (2026-07-19): now takes currentTimestamp, the real
// wall-clock time of this publish, so createProposal can bound how old the
// snapshot backing a NEW proposal is allowed to be — see
// lastSnapshotTimestamp/maxSnapshotAge's own declaration comments.
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Compact security-review pass — Critical): every
// circuit in this file that took a caller-supplied currentTimestamp used to
// trust it outright, with zero binding to real chain time. Since every
// ballot-lifecycle gate (createProposal/castVote/finalizeProposal/
// checkSilenceLock/the break-glass window, plus the two governor-attested
// clocks here) is ultimately checked against currentTimestamp, an attacker
// holding >=5% tokens could fabricate an entire internally-consistent but
// fictional create->vote->finalize sequence in a single real block,
// completely bypassing the real 72-hour community window (full governance
// takeover: treasury drain via FundAllocation, forced SilenceLockTrigger,
// LP/DEX authority redirect). Fixed by requiring every currentTimestamp to
// fall within a 1-hour band ending at real chain time — same
// blockTimeGte/blockTimeLte idiom lp_escrow.compact's sealLock already uses
// (see that circuit's own comment for the "why a window, not exact
// equality" reasoning: block-time granularity + tx propagation lag).
export circuit updateBalanceSnapshot(newRoot: Bytes<32>, currentTimestamp: Uint<64>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can update balance snapshot");
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp >= lastSnapshotTimestamp), "currentTimestamp cannot go backwards");
  balanceSnapshotRoot = disclose(newRoot);
  lastSnapshotTimestamp = disclose(currentTimestamp);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — CREATOR ACTIVITY TRACKING
// ============================================================================

// Governor updates creator's last activity timestamp
// This is called when the creator claims fees OR when a social post is detected
// (off-chain monitoring by the platform)
// T36 fix (2026-07-12): also refreshes hasClaimableBalance in the same call —
// both facts come from the same off-chain observation of the real fee-holding
// contract, so there's no reason to split them into a separate governor call.
// Break-glass fix (2026-07-19): added currentTimestamp, the real wall-clock
// time of THIS call — distinct from `timestamp` (the creator's attested
// activity time, which can legitimately stay unchanged call after call).
// Tracked separately as lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp so
// resolveBreakGlassChallenge can tell a genuinely unresponsive governor
// (this value never advances) from one who keeps checking in and honestly
// reporting no change.
export circuit updateCreatorActivity(timestamp: Uint<64>, hasClaimableBalance_: Boolean, currentTimestamp: Uint<64>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can update creator activity");
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): currentTimestamp is this call's real wall-clock
  // time and resolveBreakGlassChallenge's "governorResponded" check depends
  // on it being genuine — bind it the same way as every other entry point.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );
  assert(disclose(timestamp <= currentTimestamp), "Activity timestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(disclose(timestamp >= lastCreatorActivity), "Activity timestamp cannot go backwards");
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp >= lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp), "currentTimestamp cannot go backwards");
  lastCreatorActivity = disclose(timestamp);
  hasClaimableBalance = disclose(hasClaimableBalance_);
  lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp = disclose(currentTimestamp);
}

// Check if creator has been silent for the silence threshold
// Returns true if (currentTimestamp - lastCreatorActivity) >= silenceThreshold
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): bound currentTimestamp to real chain time so a
// caller can't misreport silence status to an off-chain consumer of this
// query — same band idiom as every other circuit in this file.
export circuit checkSilenceLock(currentTimestamp: Uint<64>): Boolean {
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );
  const elapsed = (currentTimestamp - lastCreatorActivity) as Uint<64>;
  return disclose(elapsed >= silenceThreshold);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — PROPOSAL CREATION
// ============================================================================

// Create a new governance proposal
// Anyone can propose — the community decides via voting
export circuit createProposal(
  proposalType: ProposalType,
  descriptionHash: Bytes<32>,
  currentTimestamp: Uint<64>,
  targetDexAddr: Bytes<32>,
  allocationAmount: Uint<128>,
  allocationRecipient: Bytes<32>,
  proposedCommunityWallet: Bytes<32>
): Bytes<32> {
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Critical): bind currentTimestamp to real chain
  // time before it's used for any of this circuit's own checks (snapshot
  // staleness, post-graduation delay, cooldown, silence) or stored as the
  // proposal's startTimestamp/endTimestamp — see the file header and
  // updateBalanceSnapshot's comment for the full finding.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );

  // Security audit fix: a proposal can't be voted on meaningfully until a
  // real balance snapshot exists — without this, balanceSnapshotRoot would
  // still be the zero-value from deploy and no voter could ever construct
  // a valid Merkle proof against it.
  assert(disclose(balanceSnapshotRoot != pad(32, "")), "No balance snapshot published yet");
  // Stale-snapshot fix (2026-07-19): existence alone isn't enough — a
  // snapshot published once and never refreshed would let every future
  // proposal weight votes against real holdings that have long since
  // drifted. See lastSnapshotTimestamp/maxSnapshotAge's declaration
  // comments for the full reasoning.
  const snapshotAge = (currentTimestamp - lastSnapshotTimestamp) as Uint<64>;
  assert(disclose(snapshotAge <= maxSnapshotAge), "Balance snapshot too stale — governor must republish");

  // Must be after minimum post-graduation delay
  const minProposalTime = (graduationTimestamp + minPostGradDelay) as Uint<64>;
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp >= minProposalTime), "Too soon after graduation");

  // Cooldown must have passed since last proposal ended
  if (disclose(lastProposalEnd > 0)) {
    const cooldownEnd = (lastProposalEnd + cooldownDuration) as Uint<64>;
    assert(disclose(currentTimestamp >= cooldownEnd), "Cooldown period active");
  }

  // SilenceLockTrigger requires creator to be MIA
  if (disclose(proposalType == ProposalType.SilenceLockTrigger)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.PreCTO), "CTO already triggered");
    const elapsed = (currentTimestamp - lastCreatorActivity) as Uint<64>;
    assert(disclose(elapsed >= silenceThreshold), "Creator not silent long enough");
    // T36 fix (2026-07-12): a zero-volume launch has no fee balance to
    // recover — don't let the community spend a vote on nothing.
    assert(disclose(hasClaimableBalance), "No claimable balance — nothing to recover via CTO");
    // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Low): reject an empty proposedCommunityWallet
    // up front — same footgun class as bonding_curve.compact/lp_escrow.
    // compact's triggerCTO empty-address guards; catching it here means a
    // bad proposal never even reaches a vote.
    assert(disclose(proposedCommunityWallet != pad(32, "")), "proposedCommunityWallet cannot be empty");
  }

  // DissolveCTO requires CTO to be triggered
  if (disclose(proposalType == ProposalType.DissolveCTO)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO not triggered");
  }

  // FundAllocation / DexMigration / WhitelistUpdate require CTO to be active
  if (disclose(proposalType == ProposalType.FundAllocation)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO not active");
    // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Low): same empty-address guard for the fund
    // recipient — this circuit only tracks intent (see the file's own note
    // that real fund movement is a separate off-chain-orchestrated
    // transaction), but an empty recipient here would still make that
    // downstream transaction unroutable.
    assert(disclose(allocationRecipient != pad(32, "")), "allocationRecipient cannot be empty");
  }
  if (disclose(proposalType == ProposalType.DexMigration)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO not active");
  }
  if (disclose(proposalType == ProposalType.WhitelistUpdate)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO not active");
  }

  // Derive proposer identity
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const proposer = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);

  // Compute proposal ID
  const proposalId = computeProposalId(
    proposer.bytes,
    launchId,
    descriptionHash,
    currentTimestamp
  );

  // Ensure proposal doesn't already exist
  assert(disclose(!proposals.member(disclose(proposalId))), "Proposal already exists");

  // Compute ballot end time
  const endTime = (currentTimestamp + ballotDuration) as Uint<64>;

  // Store the proposal
  proposals.insert(disclose(proposalId), disclose(Proposal {
    proposalType: proposalType,
    proposerKey: proposer.bytes,
    descriptionHash: descriptionHash,
    startTimestamp: currentTimestamp,
    endTimestamp: endTime,
    yesVotes: 0,
    noVotes: 0,
    voterCount: 0,
    state: ProposalState.Active,
    creatorYesVotes: 0,
    creatorNoVotes: 0,
    targetDexAddr: targetDexAddr,
    allocationAmount: allocationAmount,
    allocationRecipient: allocationRecipient,
    proposedCommunityWallet: proposedCommunityWallet,
    balanceSnapshotRoot: balanceSnapshotRoot
  }));

  proposalCount.increment(1);

  return disclose(proposalId);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — VOTING
// ============================================================================

// Cast a vote on a proposal
// Design requirement: voteWeight and isCreator used to be
// free caller-supplied parameters, justified by a comment claiming
// "verified via transaction merging with bonding curve PSM" — a mechanism
// that does not exist (Compact has no cross-contract calls; see
// witnesses.ts's cross-PSM composition note). A single caller could
// previously supply an arbitrary voteWeight and single-handedly satisfy
// quorum + majority on any proposal. Fixed via a governor-published
// balance-snapshot Merkle tree (see balanceSnapshotRoot/
// updateBalanceSnapshot): the voter proves their own (identity, balance)
// leaf against the root pinned on this proposal at creation time, and
// isCreator is derived by comparing the voter's own identity to the
// pinned creatorKey rather than trusting a self-declared flag.
// The vote is private via nullifier pattern — which way you voted is not
// linkable to your identity.
export circuit castVote(
  proposalId: Bytes<32>,
  support: Boolean,
  currentTimestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Critical): bind currentTimestamp to real chain
  // time before it's used to check the ballot window below — without this,
  // a caller could claim any currentTimestamp within [proposal.startTimestamp,
  // proposal.endTimestamp] regardless of real elapsed time.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );

  // Proposal must exist and be active
  assert(disclose(proposals.member(disclose(proposalId))), "Proposal not found");
  const proposal = proposals.lookup(disclose(proposalId));
  assert(disclose(proposal.state == ProposalState.Active), "Proposal not active");

  // Must be within ballot window
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp >= proposal.startTimestamp), "Voting not started");
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp <= proposal.endTimestamp), "Voting ended");

  // Derive voter identity
  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const voter = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);

  // Compute vote nullifier — prevents double-voting
  const nullifier = computeVoteNullifier(voter.bytes, launchId, proposalId);
  assert(disclose(!voteNullifiers.member(disclose(nullifier))), "Already voted on this proposal");
  voteNullifiers.insert(disclose(nullifier));

  // Security audit fix: real vote weight, proven via Merkle membership
  // against the proposal's pinned balance-snapshot root instead of trusted
  // as a bare parameter.
  const balance = getBalanceLeafAmount();
  assert(disclose(balance > 0), "Must have tokens to vote");

  const leaf = persistentHash<BalanceLeafInput>(BalanceLeafInput {
    domain: pad(32, "noctis:cto:balance:leaf:v1"),
    voterKey: voter.bytes,
    balance: balance
  });
  const proof = getBalanceProof();
  const recomputedRoot = fold(
    (acc: Bytes<32>, entry: MerkleProofEntry): Bytes<32> => {
      const left = disclose(entry.goesLeft) ? acc : entry.sibling;
      const right = disclose(entry.goesLeft) ? entry.sibling : acc;
      return hashBalanceNode(left, right);
    },
    leaf,
    proof
  );
  assert(disclose(recomputedRoot == proposal.balanceSnapshotRoot), "Invalid balance proof");

  const voteWeight = balance;

  // Security audit fix: isCreator derived in-circuit, never self-declared.
  const isCreator = disclose(voter.bytes == creatorKey);

  // T35: Cap creator vote weight (creatorVoteCap is pre-computed off-chain,
  // see the constructor and the field's declaration comment)
  const creatorCap = creatorVoteCap;
  const effectiveWeight = isCreator
    ? (disclose(voteWeight <= creatorCap) ? voteWeight : creatorCap)
    : voteWeight;

  // Update vote counts
  const newYesVotes = (proposal.yesVotes + (support ? effectiveWeight : 0)) as Uint<128>;
  const newNoVotes = (proposal.noVotes + (support ? 0 : effectiveWeight)) as Uint<128>;
  const newVoterCount = (proposal.voterCount + 1) as Uint<64>;

  // Track creator votes separately for audit (T35)
  const creatorYesAdd = (support && isCreator) ? effectiveWeight : 0;
  const creatorNoAdd = (!support && isCreator) ? effectiveWeight : 0;
  const newCreatorYes = (proposal.creatorYesVotes + creatorYesAdd) as Uint<128>;
  const newCreatorNo = (proposal.creatorNoVotes + creatorNoAdd) as Uint<128>;

  proposals.insert(disclose(proposalId), disclose(Proposal {
    proposalType: proposal.proposalType,
    proposerKey: proposal.proposerKey,
    descriptionHash: proposal.descriptionHash,
    startTimestamp: proposal.startTimestamp,
    endTimestamp: proposal.endTimestamp,
    yesVotes: newYesVotes,
    noVotes: newNoVotes,
    voterCount: newVoterCount,
    state: proposal.state,
    creatorYesVotes: newCreatorYes,
    creatorNoVotes: newCreatorNo,
    targetDexAddr: proposal.targetDexAddr,
    allocationAmount: proposal.allocationAmount,
    allocationRecipient: proposal.allocationRecipient,
    proposedCommunityWallet: proposal.proposedCommunityWallet,
    balanceSnapshotRoot: proposal.balanceSnapshotRoot
  }));
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — PROPOSAL FINALIZATION
// ============================================================================

// Finalize a proposal after the ballot window closes
// Anyone can call this — the result is deterministic
export circuit finalizeProposal(
  proposalId: Bytes<32>,
  currentTimestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Critical): bind currentTimestamp to real chain
  // time — without this, a just-created proposal could be finalized
  // immediately by claiming a currentTimestamp already past endTimestamp.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );

  // Proposal must exist
  assert(disclose(proposals.member(disclose(proposalId))), "Proposal not found");
  const proposal = proposals.lookup(disclose(proposalId));
  assert(disclose(proposal.state == ProposalState.Active), "Proposal not active");

  // Ballot window must have closed
  assert(disclose(currentTimestamp > proposal.endTimestamp), "Ballot still open");

  // Calculate total votes
  const totalVotes = (proposal.yesVotes + proposal.noVotes) as Uint<128>;

  // Check quorum: totalVotes >= totalSupply * quorumBps / 10000
  // Verify via multiplication: totalVotes * 10000 >= totalSupply * quorumBps
  const quorumCheck = (totalSupply * quorumBps as Uint<128>) as Uint<128>;
  const quorumMet = (totalVotes * 10000) as Uint<128>;
  const passedQuorum = disclose(quorumMet >= quorumCheck);

  // Check majority: yesVotes > noVotes
  const passedMajority = disclose(proposal.yesVotes > proposal.noVotes);

  // Proposal passes if both quorum AND majority
  const passed = disclose(passedQuorum && passedMajority);

  // Update proposal state
  const newState = passed ? ProposalState.Passed : ProposalState.Failed;
  proposals.insert(disclose(proposalId), disclose(Proposal {
    proposalType: proposal.proposalType,
    proposerKey: proposal.proposerKey,
    descriptionHash: proposal.descriptionHash,
    startTimestamp: proposal.startTimestamp,
    endTimestamp: proposal.endTimestamp,
    yesVotes: proposal.yesVotes,
    noVotes: proposal.noVotes,
    voterCount: proposal.voterCount,
    state: newState,
    creatorYesVotes: proposal.creatorYesVotes,
    creatorNoVotes: proposal.creatorNoVotes,
    targetDexAddr: proposal.targetDexAddr,
    allocationAmount: proposal.allocationAmount,
    allocationRecipient: proposal.allocationRecipient,
    proposedCommunityWallet: proposal.proposedCommunityWallet,
    balanceSnapshotRoot: proposal.balanceSnapshotRoot
  }));

  // Update last proposal end time (for cooldown)
  lastProposalEnd = disclose(proposal.endTimestamp);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — PROPOSAL EXECUTION
// ============================================================================

// Execute a passed proposal
// This is where the actual state changes happen
// Design requirement: communityWalletAddr is never accepted as
// a free execution-time parameter with no binding to what the community
// actually voted on — whoever called executeProposal first chose the
// wallet. Now read from proposal.proposedCommunityWallet, pinned at
// createProposal time, before any voting happened. Still permissionless —
// same "the passed state is the authorization" idiom used elsewhere
// (ExpireCurve, Graduate) — because the payload itself can no longer be
// changed by whoever calls this.
export circuit executeProposal(
  proposalId: Bytes<32>
): [] {
  // Proposal must exist and be passed
  assert(disclose(proposals.member(disclose(proposalId))), "Proposal not found");
  const proposal = proposals.lookup(disclose(proposalId));
  assert(disclose(proposal.state == ProposalState.Passed), "Proposal not passed");

  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Medium): executeProposal never re-validated
  // ctoState at execution time — only createProposal checked it, at
  // creation. Two proposals can both be validly created while ctoState
  // satisfies each one's own creation-time requirement, then execute out
  // of order (or twice): e.g. two SilenceLockTrigger proposals both created
  // while PreCTO, both passed, then both executed back-to-back — the
  // second execution would silently overwrite the first's communityWallet
  // with no error, even though the first execution had already legitimately
  // set it. Re-checking here means only the proposal whose expected
  // pre-state still actually holds can execute; a stale second proposal
  // now correctly fails instead of silently corrupting state.
  if (disclose(proposal.proposalType == ProposalType.SilenceLockTrigger)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.PreCTO), "CTO state changed since this proposal passed");
    // Trigger CTO — set community wallet and state
    ctoState = CtoState.CTOTriggered;
    communityWallet = disclose(proposal.proposedCommunityWallet);
  }

  if (disclose(proposal.proposalType == ProposalType.DissolveCTO)) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO state changed since this proposal passed");
    // Dissolve CTO — return control to creator
    // Only if creator has returned and is active again
    ctoState = CtoState.PreCTO;
    communityWallet = disclose(pad(32, ""));
  }

  // FundAllocation/DexMigration/WhitelistUpdate: this circuit only flips
  // THIS contract's own ctoState/communityWallet and marks the proposal
  // executed. The actual fund movement / DEX change / whitelist update on
  // creator_escrow PSM or lp_escrow PSM requires a SEPARATE, individually-
  // submitted transaction calling that PSM's own equivalent circuit
  // (triggerCTO, etc.) — Compact has no cross-contract call mechanism
  // (confirmed T2/T25), so nothing here can invoke those PSMs directly.
  // Phase 4 finding (2026-07-12): for Tier C specifically, this matters more
  // than it looks — bonding_curve.compact (which now holds the REAL
  // claimable creator/treasury fees, not creator_escrow.compact — see T46)
  // has no ctoState-awareness or triggerCTO circuit at all, so even a
  // faithfully-executed off-chain trigger call has nothing to redirect on
  // the contract that actually matters. Tracked as a real gap, not yet fixed.
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): these three types also required
  // ctoState == CTOTriggered at createProposal time — re-validated here
  // too, same staleness reasoning as the two branches above.
  if (
    disclose(
      proposal.proposalType == ProposalType.FundAllocation ||
      proposal.proposalType == ProposalType.DexMigration ||
      proposal.proposalType == ProposalType.WhitelistUpdate
    )
  ) {
    assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO state changed since this proposal passed");
  }

  // Mark proposal as executed
  proposals.insert(disclose(proposalId), disclose(Proposal {
    proposalType: proposal.proposalType,
    proposerKey: proposal.proposerKey,
    descriptionHash: proposal.descriptionHash,
    startTimestamp: proposal.startTimestamp,
    endTimestamp: proposal.endTimestamp,
    yesVotes: proposal.yesVotes,
    noVotes: proposal.noVotes,
    voterCount: proposal.voterCount,
    state: ProposalState.Executed,
    creatorYesVotes: proposal.creatorYesVotes,
    creatorNoVotes: proposal.creatorNoVotes,
    targetDexAddr: proposal.targetDexAddr,
    allocationAmount: proposal.allocationAmount,
    allocationRecipient: proposal.allocationRecipient,
    proposedCommunityWallet: proposal.proposedCommunityWallet,
    balanceSnapshotRoot: proposal.balanceSnapshotRoot
  }));
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — VIEW / READ
// ============================================================================

// Get CTO state
export circuit getCtoState(): CtoState {
  return ctoState;
}

// Get community wallet address
export circuit getCommunityWallet(): Bytes<32> {
  return communityWallet;
}

// Get creator's last activity timestamp
export circuit getLastCreatorActivity(): Uint<64> {
  return lastCreatorActivity;
}

// Get whether the launch currently has a claimable fee balance (T36)
export circuit getHasClaimableBalance(): Boolean {
  return hasClaimableBalance;
}

// Get proposal details
export circuit getProposal(proposalId: Bytes<32>): Proposal {
  assert(disclose(proposals.member(disclose(proposalId))), "Proposal not found");
  return disclose(proposals.lookup(disclose(proposalId)));
}

// Check if a voter has already voted on a proposal
export circuit hasVoted(
  voterKey: Bytes<32>,
  proposalId: Bytes<32>
): Boolean {
  const nullifier = computeVoteNullifier(voterKey, launchId, proposalId);
  return disclose(voteNullifiers.member(disclose(nullifier)));
}

// Get proposal count
export circuit getProposalCount(): Uint<64> {
  return proposalCount.read();
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — BREAK-GLASS FALLBACK
// ============================================================================
// See the file header's BREAK-GLASS FALLBACK note for the full design.

// Open a bonded challenge asserting hasClaimableBalance should be true,
// bypassing the governor's withheld attestation. Anyone can call this —
// same permissionless-with-skin-in-the-game pattern as the platform's
// other bonded challenges (NHOP_CHALLENGE_BOND).
export circuit bondedSilenceChallenge(
  bondAmount: Uint<128>,
  currentTimestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Critical): bind currentTimestamp to real chain
  // time — it's both used for the silence-elapsed check below and stored as
  // challengeTimestamp, which resolveBreakGlassChallenge's response window
  // is computed from.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );
  assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.PreCTO), "CTO already triggered");
  assert(disclose(!hasClaimableBalance), "hasClaimableBalance already true — no need to challenge");
  assert(
    disclose(breakGlassChallenge.state != BreakGlassState.Pending),
    "A break-glass challenge is already pending"
  );
  assert(disclose(bondAmount >= breakGlassBondMin), "Bond below minimum");

  // Silence itself is independently, publicly verifiable via elapsed real
  // time against lastCreatorActivity — break-glass bypasses the withheld
  // hasClaimableBalance attestation only, never the silence timer itself.
  const elapsed = (currentTimestamp - lastCreatorActivity) as Uint<64>;
  assert(disclose(elapsed >= silenceThreshold), "Creator not silent long enough");

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const challenger = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(challenger.bytes != pad(32, "")), "Invalid challenger key");

  // Real, ledger-enforced NIGHT bond — same receiveUnshielded pattern as
  // eligibility_gate.compact's DarkVeil bonds (T40).
  receiveUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(bondAmount));

  breakGlassChallenge = disclose(BreakGlassChallenge {
    challenger: challenger.bytes,
    bondAmount: bondAmount,
    challengeTimestamp: currentTimestamp,
    state: BreakGlassState.Pending
  });
}

// Resolve a pending break-glass challenge. Permissionless and moves no
// funds to any caller-chosen address — the Rebutted path pays only the
// fixed, sealed treasuryAddr/opsAddr, and the Confirmed path only flips
// state (the challenger claims their own refund separately via
// claimBreakGlassBondRefund, identity-gated so a third party calling this
// can't redirect the challenger's bond to themselves).
// T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, High): the Rebutted branch used to forfeit the
// challenger's bond 60/40 to treasuryAddr/opsAddr — but governorResponded
// and stillUnsupported are BOTH fully governor-controlled (a governor
// withholding hasClaimableBalance in bad faith only needs to call
// updateCreatorActivity, a free, routine, always-available call, to
// "rebut" any challenge), and treasuryAddr/opsAddr are platform-controlled
// addresses — the SAME party as the governor. That made every break-glass
// challenge against a dishonest governor a guaranteed, costless profit for
// that same governor's own platform: confiscate the bond, and the false
// hasClaimableBalance withholding continues unchallenged. This didn't just
// fail to fix the underlying single-point-of-failure (governor-censorship
// risk is separately tracked, see the file header's T97 note, and can't be
// fully closed without an on-chain oracle this codebase doesn't have) — it
// actively made the community's only recourse mechanism a net loss to use
// against exactly the adversary it exists to check. Fixed by removing the
// forfeiture destination's conflict of interest: a Rebutted challenge no
// longer pays anyone — the full bond remains refundable to the ORIGINAL
// CHALLENGER via claimBreakGlassBondRefund (extended below to accept the
// Rebutted state, not just Confirmed). A genuine governor rebuttal still
// correctly blocks the false-positive hasClaimableBalance flip; the
// challenger just isn't financially punished for a good-faith attempt
// judged by the very party it's checking.
export circuit resolveBreakGlassChallenge(
  currentTimestamp: Uint<64>
): [] {
  // T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21, Critical): bind currentTimestamp to real chain
  // time — the Undefended branch below requires currentTimestamp to be past
  // the response window, which is only a real guarantee if currentTimestamp
  // itself is genuine.
  assert(blockTimeGte(disclose(currentTimestamp)), "currentTimestamp cannot be in the future");
  assert(
    blockTimeLte(disclose((currentTimestamp + 3600) as Uint<64>)),
    "currentTimestamp too far in the past"
  );
  assert(disclose(breakGlassChallenge.state == BreakGlassState.Pending), "No pending break-glass challenge");

  const challenger = breakGlassChallenge.challenger;
  const bond = breakGlassChallenge.bondAmount;
  const challengeTimestamp = breakGlassChallenge.challengeTimestamp;
  const windowEnd = (challengeTimestamp + breakGlassResponseWindow) as Uint<64>;

  // A governor who has touched updateCreatorActivity since the challenge
  // was opened, and whose most current attestation still says no claimable
  // balance exists, counts as a real rebuttal — whether that update landed
  // inside the response window or arrived late is irrelevant to whether
  // it's genuine information; only silence (this branch never triggering
  // at all before the window elapses) means true unresponsiveness.
  const governorResponded = disclose(lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp >= challengeTimestamp);
  const stillUnsupported = disclose(!hasClaimableBalance);

  if (disclose(governorResponded && stillUnsupported)) {
    // Rebutted — T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): no forfeiture, no payout here.
    // The bond stays intact and refundable to the original challenger via
    // claimBreakGlassBondRefund (see this circuit's own header comment).
    breakGlassChallenge = disclose(BreakGlassChallenge {
      challenger: challenger,
      bondAmount: bond,
      challengeTimestamp: challengeTimestamp,
      state: BreakGlassState.Rebutted
    });
  } else {
    assert(disclose(currentTimestamp > windowEnd), "Governor's response window has not elapsed yet");

    // Undefended — the community's bonded assertion substitutes for the
    // governor's withheld attestation. This is the actual "break glass."
    hasClaimableBalance = true;
    breakGlassChallenge = disclose(BreakGlassChallenge {
      challenger: challenger,
      bondAmount: bond,
      challengeTimestamp: challengeTimestamp,
      state: BreakGlassState.Confirmed
    });
  }
}

// Claim a refund for a CONFIRMED or REBUTTED break-glass challenge's bond.
// Identity-gated to the original challenger — resolveBreakGlassChallenge
// above is deliberately permissionless but pays no one directly for this
// reason. T-AUDIT fix (2026-07-21): Rebutted now also refunds in full (no
// forfeiture) — see resolveBreakGlassChallenge's own comment for why.
export circuit claimBreakGlassBondRefund(recipientAddr: Bytes<32>): [] {
  assert(
    disclose(breakGlassChallenge.state == BreakGlassState.Confirmed || breakGlassChallenge.state == BreakGlassState.Rebutted),
    "Challenge not resolved to a refundable state"
  );
  assert(disclose(recipientAddr != pad(32, "")), "Recipient address cannot be empty");

  const sk = getUserSecret();
  const caller = deriveUserPublicKey(sk);
  assert(disclose(caller.bytes == breakGlassChallenge.challenger), "Only the original challenger can claim this refund");

  const bond = breakGlassChallenge.bondAmount;
  assert(disclose(bond > 0), "Bond already claimed");

  // Clear before paying out (checks-effects-interactions, same pattern as
  // claimBondRefund/claimRatioBondRefund elsewhere in this codebase).
  breakGlassChallenge = disclose(BreakGlassChallenge {
    challenger: breakGlassChallenge.challenger,
    bondAmount: 0,
    challengeTimestamp: breakGlassChallenge.challengeTimestamp,
    state: breakGlassChallenge.state
  });

  const dest = right<ContractAddress, UserAddress>(disclose(UserAddress { bytes: recipientAddr }));
  sendUnshielded(nativeToken(), disclose(bond), dest);
}

// Get the current (or most recently resolved) break-glass challenge.
export circuit getBreakGlassChallenge(): BreakGlassChallenge {
  return disclose(breakGlassChallenge);
}

// ============================================================================
// CIRCUITS — ADMIN / GOVERNOR
// ============================================================================

// Governor can set community wallet in emergency (e.g., compromise detected)
export circuit emergencySetCommunityWallet(wallet: Bytes<32>): [] {
  const govSecret = getGovernorSecret();
  const govKey = deriveGovernorKey(govSecret);
  assert(disclose(govKey == governorKey), "Only governor can set community wallet");
  assert(disclose(ctoState == CtoState.CTOTriggered), "CTO not triggered");
  communityWallet = disclose(wallet);
}

// ============================================================================
// PRIVACY ANALYSIS
// ============================================================================
//
// What goes ON-CHAIN (public ledger):
//   - launchId, totalSupply, graduationTimestamp (sealed at deploy)
//   - silenceThreshold, cooldownDuration, minPostGradDelay, ballotDuration, quorumBps (sealed)
//   - ctoState (public for transparency)
//   - communityWallet (public — community needs to know where funds go)
//   - lastCreatorActivity (public — community needs to see if creator is active)
//   - hasClaimableBalance (public — community needs to see whether a
//     SilenceLockTrigger would even have anything to recover, T36)
//   - proposals (public — proposal details, vote counts, state)
//   - voteNullifiers (set of nullifier hashes — prevents double-voting)
//   - lastProposalEnd (public — for cooldown transparency)
//   - governorKey (derived, not raw secret)
//   - breakGlassBondMin, breakGlassResponseWindow (sealed — the bond floor
//     and response window are public policy, known before anyone commits
//     a bond)
//   - treasuryAddr, opsAddr (sealed — fixed platform payout addresses)
//   - lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp (public — community needs to see whether
//     the governor is genuinely engaged, the whole point of break-glass)
//   - breakGlassChallenge (public — challenger identity, bond amount,
//     timestamp, and state are all public; a break-glass challenge is
//     itself a public accountability signal, not something to hide)
//   - lastSnapshotTimestamp, maxSnapshotAge (public — the community needs
//     to see whether the current balanceSnapshotRoot is actually fresh
//     enough to trust for a new proposal, same transparency rationale as
//     lastGovernorUpdateTimestamp)
//
// What stays PRIVATE:
//   - User's secret key (getUserSecret witness)
//   - Governor's secret key (getGovernorSecret witness)
//   - The voter's IDENTITY behind any single vote (nullifier is a one-way,
//     unlinkable value — it proves a specific secret voted, without
//     revealing which real-world identity holds that secret)
//   - Mapping from UserPublicKey to real-world identity
//
// Privacy notes:
//   - Vote nullifiers are unique per (voter, launch, proposal) — prevent
//     double-voting without revealing which voter is associated with which nullifier
//   - The community wallet is public by design (transparency for fund routing)
//
// T-AUDIT correction (2026-07-21, Medium): this section previously also
// claimed vote DIRECTION itself was private ("which way a voter voted...
// not how", "individual votes are not linkable to voter identity" implying
// the vote itself was hidden too). That overstates what castVote actually
// does. Every castVote call writes the FULL updated yesVotes/noVotes/
// voterCount to the public `proposals` Map, unconditionally, on every
// single call — so an observer watching that ONE transaction can trivially
// compute the exact weight and direction of THAT vote by diffing the
// proposal's state immediately before and after the call, with zero
// cryptography needed. What genuinely stays hidden is only the voter's
// IDENTITY (which real-world key cast that vote) — not the vote itself.
// This is a materially weaker guarantee than a real privacy-preserving
// tally (e.g. homomorphic aggregation, where individual transactions
// reveal nothing until an aggregate reveal step) and was not something
// this session attempted to fix — closing it for real would need a
// different vote-aggregation design, tracked as a follow-up rather than
// attempted as a quick patch here.
// ============================================================================
